    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="386"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d386">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.77/743</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Secretary of War</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="55" xml:id="d386fn55">For the attention of Wallace Murray, Director of
                        the Office of Near Eastern and African Affairs.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-20">20 May
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The War Department has received a message from the Commanding General, Persian
                    Gulf Command, which expands on State Department Message No. 350 of 19 May 44
                    from Teheran. General Connolly believes that the proposed railroad agreement
                    would endanger harmonious relations between U.S. and Russia in the Persian
                    Corridor, and that as dilatory action would probably be resorted to by the
                    Russians, nothing could actually be accomplished by pushing the agreement. It
                    appears from the above two messages that both Mr. Ford and General Connolly are
                    in agreement as to the undesirability of forcing an agreement.</p>
                <p>The above message introduced nothing to change the War Department view from that
                    portrayed in a letter from the Secretary of War to the Secretary of State dated
                    8 April 1944<note n="56" xml:id="d386fn56">Not printed.</note> when it was
                    stated that <pb facs="0391" n="379" xml:id="pg_379"/> “the War Department does
                    not see any reason to enter into the proposed agreement”.</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of War: <lb/>
                    <signed>H. R. <hi rend="smallcaps">Maddux</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Colonel, G.S.C.</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
